## Product vision

The player is Amelia, a friendly original blue city bus who lives at a mechanic’s garage with her caretaker, “Mechanic Mom.”

The game should feel like a warm animated children’s show crossed with a simple open-world driving adventure:

- Drive through small, cheerful neighborhoods.
- Pick up and drop off friendly animal passengers.
- Follow route arrows and learn where to turn.
- Practice stop/go, red lights, green lights, left/right, bus stops, and basic road signs.
- Earn stars, stickers, collectibles, garage decorations, and cosmetic bus upgrades.
- Return to the garage between adventures.
- Include small story episodes: first day driving, lost puppy, parade day, beach trip, rainy-day rescue, helping friends get somewhere important.
- Include Free Drive eventually, but structured story adventures should be the main game.
- The tone should be gentle, funny, safe, encouraging, and never punishing.

The game must be an original IP. Do not use Tayo, Pixar, Cars, or other existing character names, designs, logos, voices, or visual imitation. Amelia may be a cute anthropomorphic bus, but she needs her own recognizable personality and visual identity.

## Primary platform

Target: Apple TV / tvOS first.

This must be a real native tvOS game, not:

- a webview
- a PWA
- a Capacitor wrapper
- a browser shell
- a thin conversion of the existing HTML/Three.js project

The game should work well on a living-room TV in 1080p and 4K.

Primary control assumptions:

- Siri Remote must be supported for the core experience.
- MFi / PlayStation / Xbox controller support should also be supported and should feel better for driving.
- Do not make a controller mandatory for the first playable story.
- Design a remote-friendly driving model rather than trying to force full analog driving onto the Siri Remote.

For example, consider assisted driving, lane guidance, slow child-friendly steering, auto-forward movement in some story moments, simple braking/stopping interactions, and route decisions that work with clickpad directions.

## Audience and design principles

Primary player: approximately ages 3–6.

Design requirements:

- Very large readable UI.
- Minimal reading required.
- Spoken guidance in English and Spanish.
- Strong visual route guidance.
- Immediate positive feedback.
- No failure states that feel harsh.
- No long menus or complicated settings.
- Short gameplay loops with a satisfying conclusion.
- Parent can play alongside child with a controller.
- Child should be able to launch and understand the main activity without adult help after a little familiarity.

## Privacy and business constraints

This should be a private/family-first project initially, with the option to submit publicly later.

Assume:

- No ads.
- No analytics.
- No accounts.
- No chat.
- No external links visible to children.
- No purchases in the first version.
- No network dependency for normal play.
- All game state stored locally.
- A future App Store version should be compatible with Apple Kids Category expectations.

